# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gene-regulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In genetics, an **enhancer** is a short (50–1500 bp) region of DNA that can be bound by proteins (activators) to increase the likelihood that transcription of a particular gene will occur.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] These proteins are usually referred to as transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] They can be located up to 1 Mbp (1,000,000 bp) away from the gene, upstream or downstream from the start site.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] There are hundreds of thousands of enhancers in the human genome.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] They are found in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Active enhancers typically get transcribed as enhancer or regulatory non-coding RNA, whose expression levels correlate with mRNA levels of target genes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The first discovery of a eukaryotic enhancer was in the immunoglobulin heavy chain gene in 1983.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] This enhancer, located in the large intron, provided an explanation for the transcriptional activation of rearranged Vh gene promoters while unrearranged Vh promoters remained inactive.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Lately, enhancers have been shown to be involved in certain medical conditions, for example, myelosuppression.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Since 2022, scientists have used artificial intelligence to design synthetic enhancers and applied them in animal systems, first in a cell line, and one year later also in vivo.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In eukaryotic cells the structure of the chromatin complex of DNA is folded in a way that functionally mimics the supercoiled state characteristic of prokaryotic DNA, so although the enhancer DNA may be far from the gene in a linear way, it is spatially close to the promoter and gene.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] This allows it to interact with the general transcription factors and RNA polymerase II.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The same mechanism holds true for silencers in the eukaryotic genome.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Silencers are antagonists of enhancers that, when bound to its proper transcription factors called repressors, repress the transcription of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Silencers and enhancers may be in close proximity to each other or may even be in the same region only differentiated by the transcription factor the region binds to.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer may be located upstream or downstream of the gene it regulates.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Furthermore, an enhancer does not need to be located near the transcription initiation site to affect transcription, as some have been found located several hundred thousand base pairs upstream or downstream of the start site.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers do not act on the promoter region itself, but are bound by activator proteins as first shown by in vivo competition experiments.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Subsequently, molecular studies showed direct interactions with transcription factors and cofactors, including the mediator complex, which recruits polymerase II and the general transcription factors which then begin transcribing the genes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers can also be found within introns.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer's orientation may even be reversed without affecting its function; additionally, an enhancer may be excised and inserted elsewhere in the chromosome, and still affect gene transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] That is one reason that introns polymorphisms may have effects although they are not translated.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers can also be found at the exonic region of an unrelated gene and they may act on genes on another chromosome.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers are bound by p300-CBP and their location can be predicted by ChIP-seq against this family of coactivators.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Gene expression in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoters and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Core promoters are sufficient to direct transcription initiation, but generally have low basal activity.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Other important cis-regulatory modules are localized in DNA regions that are distant from the transcription start sites.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] These include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Among this constellation of elements, enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer localized in a DNA region distant from the promoter of a gene can have a very large effect on gene expression, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased expression due to an activated enhancer.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers are regions of the genome that are major gene-regulatory elements.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene expression programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] While there are hundreds of thousands of enhancer DNA regions, for a particular type of tissue only specific enhancers are brought into proximity with the promoters that they regulate.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to their target promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundreds of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and can coordinate with each other to control the expression of their common target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The schematic illustration in this section shows an enhancer looping around to come into close physical proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1), with one member of the dimer anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Mediator (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two Enhancer RNAs (eRNAs) as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Like mRNAs, these eRNAs are usually protected by their 5′ cap.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] There are numerous methods to study enhancers, such as site-directed mutagenesis, comparative genomics, or in-vitro analysis of transcription-factor binding assays (e.g.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] More recently, high-throughput methods have been established that allow scientists to analyze thousands of enhancers in parallel.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] For instance, massively parallel reporter assays (MPRAs) and self-transcribing active regulatory region sequencing (STARR-seq) have revolutionized enhancer characterization.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] However, MPRA and STARR-seq datasets generated in cell lines such as K562 found substantial inconsistencies in enhancer calls from different labs that are primarily due to technical variations in both experimental details and data processing.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] HACNS1 (also known as CENTG2 and located in the Human Accelerated Region 2) is a gene enhancer "that may have contributed to the evolution of the uniquely opposable human thumb, and possibly also modifications in the ankle or foot that allow humans to walk on two legs".
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Evidence to date shows that of the 110,000 gene enhancer sequences identified in the human genome, HACNS1 has undergone the most change during the evolution of humans following the split with the ancestors of chimpanzees.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer near the gene GADD45g has been described that may regulate brain growth in chimpanzees and other mammals, but not in humans.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The GADD45G regulator in mice and chimps is active in regions of the brain where cells that form the cortex, ventral forebrain, and thalamus are located and may suppress further neurogenesis.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Loss of the GADD45G enhancer in humans may contribute to an increase of certain neuronal populations and to forebrain expansion in humans.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The development, differentiation and growth of cells and tissues require precisely regulated patterns of gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers work as cis-regulatory elements to mediate both spatial and temporal control of development by turning on transcription in specific cells and/or repressing it in other cells.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Thus, the particular combination of transcription factors and other DNA-binding proteins in a developing tissue controls which genes will be expressed in that tissue.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers allow the same gene to be used in diverse processes in space and time.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Traditionally, enhancers were identified by enhancer trap techniques using a reporter gene or by comparative sequence analysis and computational genomics.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In genetically tractable models such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster,* for example, a reporter construct such as the *lacZ* gene can be randomly integrated into the genome using a P element transposon.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] If the reporter gene integrates near an enhancer, its expression will reflect the expression pattern driven by that enhancer.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Thus, staining the flies for LacZ expression or activity and cloning the sequence surrounding the integration site allows the identification of the enhancer sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The development of genomic and epigenomic technologies, however, has dramatically changed the outlook for cis-regulatory modules (CRM) discovery.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An example of NGS-based approach called DNase-seq have enabled identification of nucleosome-depleted, or open chromatin regions, which can contain CRM.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] More recently techniques such as ATAC-seq have been developed which require less starting material.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Nucelosome depleted regions can be identified in vivo through expression of Dam methylase, allowing for greater control of cell-type specific enhancer identification.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Computational methods include comparative genomics, clustering of known or predicted TF-binding sites, and supervised machine-learning approaches trained on known CRMs.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] All of these methods have proven effective for CRM discovery, but each has its own considerations and limitations, and each is subject to a greater or lesser number of false-positive identifications.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In the comparative genomics approach, sequence conservation of non-coding regions can be indicative of enhancers.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Sequences from multiple species are aligned, and conserved regions are identified computationally.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Although much evidence has pointed to sequence conservation for critical developmental enhancers, other work has shown that the function of enhancers can be conserved with little or no primary sequence conservation.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] For example, the *RET* enhancers in humans have very little sequence conservation to those in zebrafish, yet both species' sequences produce nearly identical patterns of reporter gene expression in zebrafish.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The enhancers determining early segmentation in *Drosophila melanogaster* embryos are among the best characterized developmental enhancers.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In the early fly embryo, the gap gene transcription factors are responsible for activating and repressing a number of segmentation genes, such as the pair rule genes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The gap genes are expressed in blocks along the anterior-posterior axis of the fly along with other maternal effect transcription factors, thus creating zones within which different combinations of transcription factors are expressed.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The pair-rule genes are separated from one another by non-expressing cells.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Moreover, the stripes of expression for different pair-rule genes are offset by a few cell diameters from one another.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Thus, unique combinations of pair-rule gene expression create spatial domains along the anterior-posterior axis to set up each of the 14 individual segments.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The 480 bp enhancer responsible for driving the sharp stripe two of the pair-rule gene *even-skipped* (*eve*) has been well-characterized.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The enhancer contains 12 different binding sites for maternal and gap gene transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Activating and repressing sites overlap in sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] *Eve* is only expressed in a narrow stripe of cells that contain high concentrations of the activators and low concentration of the repressors for this enhancer sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Other enhancer regions drive *eve* expression in 6 other stripes in the embryo.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Establishing body axes is a critical step in animal development.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] During mouse embryonic development, Nodal, a transforming growth factor-beta superfamily ligand, is a key gene involved in patterning both the anterior-posterior axis and the left-right axis of the early embryo.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The *Nodal* gene contains two enhancers: the Proximal Epiblast Enhancer (PEE) and the Asymmetric Enhancer (ASE).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The PEE is upstream of the Nodal gene and drives *Nodal* expression in the portion of the primitive streak that will differentiate into the node (also referred to as the primitive node).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The PEE turns on Nodal expression in response to a combination of Wnt signaling plus a second, unknown signal; thus, a member of the LEF/TCF transcription factor family likely binds to a TCF binding site in the cells in the node.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Diffusion of Nodal away from the node forms a gradient which then patterns the extending anterior-posterior axis of the embryo.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The ASE is an intronic enhancer bound by the fork head domain transcription factor Fox1.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Early in development, Fox1-driven Nodal expression establishes the visceral endoderm.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Later in development, Fox1 binding to the ASE drives *Nodal* expression on the left side of the lateral plate mesoderm, thus establishing left-right asymmetry necessary for asymmetric organ development in the mesoderm.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Establishing three germ layers during gastrulation is another critical step in animal development.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Each of the three germ layers has unique patterns of gene expression that promote their differentiation and development.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The endoderm is specified early in development by *Gata4* expression, and Gata4 goes on to direct gut morphogenesis later.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] *Gata4* expression is controlled in the early embryo by an intronic enhancer that binds another forkhead domain transcription factor, FoxA2.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Initially the enhancer drives broad gene expression throughout the embryo, but the expression quickly becomes restricted to the endoderm, suggesting that other repressors may be involved in its restriction.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Late in development, the same enhancer restricts expression to the tissues that will become the stomach and pancreas.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] An additional enhancer is responsible for maintaining *Gata4* expression in the endoderm during the intermediate stages of gut development.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Some genes involved in critical developmental processes contain multiple enhancers of overlapping function.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Secondary enhancers, or "shadow enhancers", may be found many kilobases away from the primary enhancer ("primary" usually refers to the first enhancer discovered, which is often closer to the gene it regulates).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] On its own, each enhancer drives nearly identical patterns of gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has shown that multiple enhancers allow fruit flies to survive environmental perturbations, such as an increase in temperature.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] When raised at an elevated temperature, a single enhancer sometimes fails to drive the complete pattern of expression, whereas the presence of both enhancers permits normal gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] One theme of research in evolutionary developmental biology ("evo-devo") is investigating the role of enhancers and other cis-regulatory elements in producing morphological changes via developmental differences between species.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has investigated the role of enhancers in morphological changes in threespine stickleback fish.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Sticklebacks exist in both marine and freshwater environments, but sticklebacks in many freshwater populations have completely lost their pelvic fins (appendages homologous to the posterior limb of tetrapods).
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] *Pitx1* is a homeobox gene involved in posterior limb development in vertebrates.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Preliminary genetic analyses indicated that changes in the expression of this gene were responsible for pelvic reduction in sticklebacks.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Fish expressing only the freshwater allele of *Pitx1* do not have pelvic spines, whereas fish expressing a marine allele retain pelvic spines.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] A more thorough characterization showed that a 500 base pair enhancer sequence is responsible for turning on *Pitx1* expression in the posterior fin bud.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] This enhancer is located near a chromosomal fragile site—a sequence of DNA that is likely to be broken and thus more likely to be mutated as a result of imprecise DNA repair.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] This fragile site has caused repeated, independent losses of the enhancer responsible for driving *Pitx1* expression in the pelvic spines in isolated freshwater population, and without this enhancer, freshwater fish fail to develop pelvic spines.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Pigmentation patterns provide one of the most striking and easily scored differences between different species of animals.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Pigmentation of the *Drosophila* wing has proven to be a particularly amenable system for studying the development of complex pigmentation phenotypes.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] The *Drosophila guttifera* wing has 12 dark pigmentation spots and 4 lighter gray intervein patches.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Pigment spots arise from expression of the *yellow* gene, whose product produces black melanin.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has shown that two enhancers in the *yellow* gene produce gene expression in precisely this pattern – the vein spot enhancer drives reporter gene expression in the 12 spots, and the intervein shade enhancer drives reporter expression in the 4 distinct patches.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] These two enhancers are responsive to the Wnt signaling pathway, which is activated by *wingless* expression at all of the pigmented locations.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Thus, in the evolution of the complex pigmentation phenotype, the *yellow* pigment gene evolved enhancers responsive to the wingless signal and *wingless* expression evolved at new locations to produce novel wing patterns.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Each cell typically contains several hundred of a special class of enhancers that stretch over many kilobases long DNA sequences, called "super-enhancers".
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] These enhancers contain a large number of binding sites for sequence-specific, inducible transcription factors, and regulate expression of genes involved in cell differentiation.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] As a result, inflammation reprograms cells, altering their interactions with the rest of tissue and with the immune system.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In cancer, proteins that control NF-κB activity are dysregulated, permitting malignant cells to decrease their dependence on interactions with local tissue, and hindering their surveillance by the immune system.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In 1980, Max Birnstiel and Rudolf Grosschedl described an enhancer, which they referred to as a “modulator”.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] In 1981, an enhancer was described that originates from the polyomavirus SV40 and contains two identical 72 bp long sections called 72-bp repeats.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] It was shown that each of the two segments has a weak enhancing effect on the promoter on its own, but together they increase the activity many times over.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Synthetic regulatory elements such as enhancers promise to be a powerful tool to direct gene products to particular cell types in order to treat disease by activating beneficial genes or by halting aberrant cell states.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Since 2022, artificial intelligence and transfer learning strategies have led to a better understanding of the features of regulatory DNA sequences, the prediction, and the design of synthetic enhancers.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Building on work in cell culture, synthetic enhancers were successfully applied to entire living organisms in 2023.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] Using deep neural networks, scientists simulated the evolution of DNA sequences to analyze the emergence of features that underlie enhancer function.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] This allowed the design and production of a range of functioning synthetic enhancers for different cell types of the fruit fly brain.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] A second approach trained artificial intelligence models on single-cell DNA accessibility data and transferred the learned models towards the prediction of enhancers for selected tissues in the fruit fly embryo.
[src:gene-regulation/enhancer-genetics] These enhancer prediction models were used to design synthetic enhancers for the nervous system, brain, muscle, epidermis and gut.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The ***lactose* operon** (***lac*** operon) is an operon required for the transport and metabolism of lactose in *E. coli* and many other enteric bacteria.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Although glucose is the preferred carbon source for most enteric bacteria, the *lac* operon allows for the effective digestion of lactose when glucose is not available through the activity of β-galactosidase.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Gene regulation of the *lac* operon was the first genetic regulatory mechanism to be understood clearly, so it has become a foremost example of prokaryotic gene regulation.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It is often discussed in introductory molecular and cellular biology classes for this reason.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This lactose metabolism system was used by François Jacob and Jacques Monod to determine how a biological cell knows which enzyme to synthesize.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Their work on the *lac* operon won them the Nobel Prize in Physiology in 1965.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Most bacterial cells including *E. coli* lack introns in their genome.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Hence the gene regulation by *lac* operon occurs at the transcriptional level, by controlling transcription of DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Bacterial operons are polycistronic transcripts that are able to produce multiple proteins from one mRNA transcript.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In this case, when lactose is required as a sugar source for the bacterium, the three genes of the *lac* operon can be transcribed and their subsequent proteins translated: *lacZ*, *lacY*, and *lacA*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The gene product of *lacZ* is β-galactosidase which cleaves lactose, a disaccharide, into glucose and galactose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] *lacY* encodes β-galactoside permease, a membrane protein which becomes embedded in the Plasma membrane to enable the cellular transport of lactose into the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Finally, *lacA* encodes β-galactoside transacetylase.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Note that the number of base pairs in diagram given above are not to scale.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] There are in fact over 5300 base pairs in the *lac* operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It would be wasteful to produce enzymes when no lactose is available or if a preferable energy source such as glucose were available.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *lac* operon uses a two-part control mechanism to ensure that the cell expends energy producing the enzymes encoded by the *lac* operon only when necessary.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In the absence of lactose, the *lac* repressor, encoded by *lacI,* halts production of the enzymes and transport proteins encoded by the *lac* operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It does so by blocking the DNA dependent RNA polymerase.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This blocking/ halting is not perfect, and a minimal amount of gene expression does take place all the time.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The repressor protein is always expressed, but the *lac* operon (i.e. enzymes and transport proteins) are almost completely repressed, allowing for a small level of background expression.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] If this weren't the case, there would be no lacY transporter protein in the cellular membrane; consequently, the *lac* operon would not be able to detect the presence of lactose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] When lactose is available but not glucose, then some lactose enters the cell using pre-existing transport protein encoded by lacY.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This lactose then combines with the repressor and inactivates it, hence allowing the *lac* operon to be expressed.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Then more β-galactoside permease is synthesized allowing even more lactose to enter and the enzymes encoded by lacZ and lacA can digest it.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] However, in the presence of glucose, regardless of the presence of lactose, the operon will be repressed.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This is because the catabolite activator protein (CAP), required for production of the enzymes, remains inactive, and EIIAGlc shuts down lactose permease to prevent transport of lactose into the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This dual control mechanism causes the sequential utilization of glucose and lactose in two distinct growth phases, known as diauxie.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Only *lacZ* and *lacY* appear to be necessary for lactose catabolic pathway.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] By numbers, *lacI* has 1100 bps, *lacZ* has 3000 bps, *lacY* has 800 bps, *lacA* has 800 bps, with 3 bps corresponding to 1 amino acid.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Three-letter abbreviations are used to describe phenotypes in bacteria including *E. coli*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In the case of Lac, wild type cells are Lac+ and are able to use lactose as a carbon and energy source, while Lac− mutant derivatives cannot use lactose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The same three letters are typically used (lower-case, italicized) to label the genes involved in a particular phenotype, where each different gene is additionally distinguished by an extra letter.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *lac* genes encoding enzymes are *lacZ*, *lacY*, and *lacA*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The fourth *lac* gene is *lacI*, encoding the lactose repressor—"I" stands for *inducibility*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] One may distinguish between *structural* genes encoding enzymes, and regulatory genes encoding proteins that affect gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Current usage expands the phenotypic nomenclature to apply to proteins: thus, LacZ is the protein product of the *lacZ* gene, β-galactosidase.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Various short sequences that are not genes also affect gene expression, including the *lac* promoter, *lac p*, and the *lac* operator, *lac o*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Although it is not strictly standard usage, mutations affecting *lac o* are referred to as *lac o*c, for historical reasons.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Specific control of the *lac* genes depends on the availability of the substrate lactose to the bacterium.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The proteins are not produced by the bacterium when lactose is unavailable as a carbon source.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *lac* genes are organized into an operon; that is, they are oriented in the same direction immediately adjacent on the chromosome and are co-transcribed into a single polycistronic mRNA molecule.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Transcription of all genes starts with the binding of the enzyme RNA polymerase (RNAP), a DNA-binding protein, which binds to a specific DNA binding site, the promoter, immediately upstream of the genes.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Binding of RNA polymerase to the promoter is aided by the cAMP-bound catabolite activator protein (CAP, also known as the cAMP receptor protein).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] However, the *lacI* gene (regulatory gene for *lac* operon) produces a protein that blocks RNAP from binding to the operator of the operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This protein can only be removed when allolactose binds to it, and inactivates it.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The protein that is formed by the *lacI* gene is known as the lac repressor.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The type of regulation that the *lac* operon undergoes is referred to as negative inducible, meaning that the gene is turned off by the regulatory factor (*lac* repressor) unless some molecule (lactose) is added.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Once the repressor is removed, RNAP then proceeds to transcribe all three genes (*lacZYA*) into mRNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Each of the three genes on the mRNA strand has its own Shine-Dalgarno sequence, so the genes are independently translated.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The DNA sequence of the *E. coli* *lac* operon, the *lacZYA* mRNA, and the *lacI* genes are available from GenBank (view).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The first control mechanism is the regulatory response to lactose, which uses an intracellular *regulatory protein* called the *lactose repressor* to hinder production of β-galactosidase in the absence of lactose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *lacI* gene coding for the repressor lies nearby the *lac* operon and is always expressed (*constitutive*).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] If lactose is missing from the growth medium, the repressor binds very tightly to a short DNA sequence just downstream of the promoter near the beginning of *lacZ* called the *lac operator*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The repressor binding to the operator interferes with binding of RNAP to the promoter, and therefore mRNA encoding LacZ and LacY is only made at very low levels.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] When cells are grown in the presence of lactose, however, a lactose metabolite called allolactose, made from lactose by the product of the *lacZ* gene, binds to the repressor, causing an allosteric shift.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Thus altered, the repressor is unable to bind to the operator, allowing RNAP to transcribe the *lac* genes and thereby leading to higher levels of the encoded proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The second control mechanism is a response to glucose, which uses the catabolite activator protein (CAP) homodimer to greatly increase production of β-galactosidase in the absence of glucose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) is a signal molecule whose prevalence is inversely proportional to that of glucose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It binds to the CAP, which in turn allows the CAP to bind to the CAP binding site (a 16 bp DNA sequence upstream of the promoter on the left in the diagram below, about 60 bp upstream of the transcription start site), which assists the RNAP in binding to the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In the absence of glucose, the cAMP concentration is high and binding of CAP-cAMP to the DNA significantly increases the production of β-galactosidase, enabling the cell to hydrolyse lactose and release galactose and glucose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] More recently inducer exclusion was shown to block expression of the *lac* operon when glucose is present.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Glucose is transported into the cell by the PEP-dependent phosphotransferase system.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The phosphate group of phosphoenolpyruvate is transferred via a phosphorylation cascade consisting of the general PTS (phosphotransferase system) proteins HPr and EIA and the glucose-specific PTS proteins EIIAGlc and EIIBGlc, the cytoplasmic domain of the EII glucose transporter.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Transport of glucose is accompanied by its phosphorylation by EIIBGlc, draining the phosphate group from the other PTS proteins, including EIIAGlc.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The unphosphorylated form of EIIAGlc binds to the *lac* permease and prevents it from bringing lactose into the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Therefore, if both glucose and lactose are present, the transport of glucose blocks the transport of the inducer of the *lac* operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The lac repressor is a four-part protein, a tetramer, with identical subunits.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Each subunit contains a helix-turn-helix (HTH) motif capable of binding to DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The operator site where repressor binds is a DNA sequence with inverted repeat symmetry.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The two DNA half-sites of the operator together bind to two of the subunits of the repressor.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Although the other two subunits of repressor are not doing anything in this model, this property was not understood for many years.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Eventually it was discovered that two additional operators are involved in *lac* regulation.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] One (O3) lies about −90 bp upstream of O1 in the end of the *lacI* gene, and the other (O2) is about +410 bp downstream of O1 in the early part of *lacZ*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] These two sites were not found in the early work because they have redundant functions and individual mutations do not affect repression very much.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Single mutations to either O2 or O3 have only 2 to 3-fold effects.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] However, their importance is demonstrated by the fact that a double mutant defective in both O2 and O3 is dramatically de-repressed (by about 70-fold).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In the current model, *lac* repressor is bound simultaneously to both the main operator O1 and to either O2 or O3.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The intervening DNA loops out from the complex.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The redundant nature of the two minor operators suggests that it is not a specific looped complex that is important.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] One idea is that the system works through tethering; if bound repressor releases from O1 momentarily, binding to a minor operator keeps it in the vicinity, so that it may rebind quickly.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This would increase the affinity of repressor for O1.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The repressor is an allosteric protein, i.e. it can assume either one of two slightly different shapes, which are in equilibrium with each other.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In one form the repressor will bind to the operator DNA with high specificity, and in the other form it has lost its specificity.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] According to the classical model of induction, binding of the inducer, either allolactose or IPTG, to the repressor affects the distribution of repressor between the two shapes.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Thus, repressor with inducer bound is stabilized in the non-DNA-binding conformation.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] However, this simple model cannot be the whole story, because repressor is bound quite stably to DNA, yet it is released rapidly by addition of inducer.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Therefore, it seems clear that an inducer can also bind to the repressor when the repressor is already bound to DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It is still not entirely known what the exact mechanism of binding is.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Non-specific binding of the repressor to DNA plays a crucial role in the repression and induction of the Lac-operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The specific binding site for the Lac-repressor protein is the operator.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The non-specific interaction is mediated mainly by charge-charge interactions while binding to the operator is reinforced by hydrophobic interactions.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Additionally, there is an abundance of non-specific DNA sequences to which the repressor can bind.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Essentially, any sequence that is not the operator, is considered non-specific.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Studies have shown, that without the presence of non-specific binding, induction (or unrepression) of the Lac-operon could not occur even with saturated levels of inducer.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It had been demonstrated that, without non-specific binding, the basal level of induction is ten thousand times smaller than observed normally.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This is because the non-specific DNA acts as sort of a "sink" for the repressor proteins, distracting them from the operator.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The non-specific sequences decrease the amount of available repressor in the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This in turn reduces the amount of inducer required to unrepress the system.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A number of lactose derivatives or analogs have been described that are useful for work with the *lac* operon.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] These compounds are mainly substituted galactosides, where the glucose moiety of lactose is replaced by another chemical group.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The experimental microorganism used by François Jacob and Jacques Monod was the common laboratory bacterium, *E. coli*, but many of the basic regulatory concepts that were discovered by Jacob and Monod are fundamental to cellular regulation in all organisms.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The key idea is that proteins are not synthesized when they are not needed—*E. coli* conserves cellular resources and energy by not making the three Lac proteins when there is no need to metabolize lactose, such as when other sugars like glucose are available.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The following section discusses how *E. coli* controls certain genes in response to metabolic needs.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] During World War II, Monod was testing the effects of combinations of sugars as nutrient sources for *E. coli* and *B. subtilis*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Monod was following up on similar studies that had been conducted by other scientists with bacteria and yeast.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] He found that bacteria grown with two different sugars often displayed two phases of growth.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] For example, if glucose and lactose were both provided, glucose was metabolized first (growth phase I, see Figure 2) and then lactose (growth phase II).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Lactose was not metabolized during the first part of the diauxic growth curve because β-galactosidase was not made when both glucose and lactose were present in the medium.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Monod then focused his attention on the induction of β-galactosidase formation that occurred when lactose was the sole sugar in the culture medium.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A conceptual breakthrough of Jacob and Monod was to recognize the distinction between regulatory substances and sites where they act to change gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A former soldier, Jacob used the analogy of a bomber that would release its lethal cargo upon receipt of a special radio transmission or signal.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A working system requires both a ground transmitter and a receiver in the airplane.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Now, suppose that the usual transmitter is broken.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This system can be made to work by introduction of a second, functional transmitter.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In contrast, he said, consider a bomber with a defective receiver.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The behavior of *this* bomber cannot be changed by introduction of a second, functional aeroplane.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] To analyze regulatory mutants of the *lac* operon, Jacob developed a system by which a second copy of the *lac* genes (*lacI* with its promoter, and *lacZYA* with promoter and operator) could be introduced into a single cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A culture of such bacteria, which are diploid for the *lac* genes but otherwise normal, is then tested for the regulatory phenotype.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In particular, it is determined whether LacZ and LacY are made even in the absence of IPTG (due to the *lactose repressor* produced by the mutant gene being non-functional).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This experiment, in which genes or gene clusters are tested pairwise, is called a *complementation test*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This test is illustrated in the figure (*lacA* is omitted for simplicity).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] First, certain haploid states are shown (i.e. the cell carries only a single copy of the *lac* genes).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Panel (a) shows repression, (b) shows induction by IPTG, and (c) and (d) show the effect of a mutation to the *lacI* gene or to the operator, respectively.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In panel (e) the complementation test for repressor is shown.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] If one copy of the *lac* genes carries a mutation in *lacI*, but the second copy is wild type for *lacI*, the resulting phenotype is normal—but lacZ is expressed when exposed to inducer IPTG.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Mutations affecting repressor are said to be *recessive* to wild type (and that wild type is *dominant*), and this is explained by the fact that repressor is a small protein which can diffuse in the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The copy of the *lac* operon adjacent to the defective *lacI* gene is effectively shut off by protein produced from the second copy of *lacI*.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] If the same experiment is carried out using an operator mutation, a different result is obtained (panel (f)).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The phenotype of a cell carrying one mutant and one wild type operator site is that LacZ and LacY are produced even in the absence of the inducer IPTG; because the damaged operator site, does not permit binding of the repressor to inhibit transcription of the structural genes.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] When the operator site where repressor must bind is damaged by mutation, the presence of a second functional site in the same cell makes no difference to expression of genes controlled by the mutant site.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] A more sophisticated version of this experiment uses *marked* operons to distinguish between the two copies of the *lac* genes and show that the unregulated structural gene(s) is(are) the one(s) next to the mutant operator (panel (g).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] For example, suppose that one copy is marked by a mutation inactivating *lacZ* so that it can only produce the LacY protein, while the second copy carries a mutation affecting *lacY* and can only produce LacZ.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In this version, only the copy of the *lac* operon that is adjacent to the mutant operator is expressed without IPTG.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] We say that the operator mutation is *cis-dominant*, it is dominant to wild type but affects only the copy of the operon which is immediately adjacent to it.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] This explanation is misleading in an important sense, because it proceeds from a description of the experiment and then explains the results in terms of a model.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] But in fact, it is often true that the model comes first, and an experiment is fashioned specifically to test the model.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Jacob and Monod first imagined that there must be a *site* in DNA with the properties of the operator, and then designed their complementation tests to show this.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The dominance of operator mutants also suggests a procedure to select them specifically.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] If regulatory mutants are selected from a culture of wild type using phenyl-Gal, as described above, operator mutations are rare compared to repressor mutants because the target-size is so small.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] But if instead we start with a strain which carries two copies of the whole *lac* region (that is diploid for *lac*), the repressor mutations (which still occur) are not recovered because complementation by the second, wild type *lacI* gene confers a wild type phenotype.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In contrast, mutation of one copy of the operator confers a mutant phenotype because it is dominant to the second, wild type copy.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Explanation of diauxie depended on the characterization of additional mutations affecting the *lac* genes other than those explained by the classical model.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Two other genes, *cya* and *crp*, subsequently were identified that mapped far from *lac*, and that, when mutated, result in a decreased level of expression in the *presence* of IPTG and even in strains of the bacterium lacking the repressor or operator.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The discovery of cAMP in *E. coli* led to the demonstration that mutants defective the *cya* gene but not the *crp* gene could be restored to full activity by the addition of cAMP to the medium.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *cya* gene encodes adenylate cyclase, which produces cAMP.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In a *cya* mutant, the absence of cAMP makes the expression of the *lacZYA* genes more than ten times lower than normal.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Addition of cAMP corrects the low Lac expression characteristic of *cya* mutants.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The second gene, *crp*, encodes a protein called catabolite activator protein (CAP) or cAMP receptor protein (CRP).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] However the lactose metabolism enzymes are made in small quantities in the presence of both glucose and lactose (sometimes called leaky expression) due to the fact that the RNAP can still sometimes bind and initiate transcription even in the absence of CAP.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Leaky expression is necessary in order to allow for metabolism of some lactose after the glucose source is expended, but before *lac* expression is fully activated.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The delay between growth phases reflects the time needed to produce sufficient quantities of lactose-metabolizing enzymes.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] First, the CAP regulatory protein has to assemble on the *lac* promoter, resulting in an increase in the production of *lac* mRNA.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] More available copies of the *lac* mRNA results in the production (see translation) of significantly more copies of LacZ (β-galactosidase, for lactose metabolism) and LacY (lactose permease to transport lactose into the cell).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] After a delay needed to increase the level of the lactose metabolizing enzymes, the bacteria enter into a new rapid phase of cell growth.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Two puzzles of catabolite repression relate to how cAMP levels are coupled to the presence of glucose, and secondly, why the cells should even bother.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] After lactose is cleaved it actually forms glucose and galactose (easily converted to glucose).
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In metabolic terms, lactose is just as *good* a carbon and energy source as glucose.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The cAMP level is related not to intracellular glucose concentration but to the rate of glucose transport, which influences the activity of adenylate cyclase.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] (In addition, glucose transport also leads to direct inhibition of the lactose permease.) As to why *E. coli* works this way, one can only speculate.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] All enteric bacteria ferment glucose, which suggests they encounter it frequently.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] It is possible that a small difference in efficiency of transport or metabolism of glucose v. lactose makes it advantageous for cells to regulate the *lac* operon in this way.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The *lac* gene and its derivatives are amenable to use as a reporter gene in a number of bacterial-based selection techniques such as two hybrid analysis, in which the successful binding of a transcriptional activator to a specific promoter sequence must be determined.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] In LB plates containing X-gal, the colour change from white colonies to a shade of blue corresponds to about 20–100 β-galactosidase units, while tetrazolium lactose and MacConkey lactose media have a range of 100–1000 units, being most sensitive in the high and low parts of this range respectively.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] Since MacConkey lactose and tetrazolium lactose media both rely on the products of lactose breakdown, they require the presence of both *lacZ* and *lacY* genes.
[src:gene-regulation/lac-operon] The many *lac* fusion techniques which include only the *lacZ* gene are thus suited to X-gal plates or ONPG liquid broths.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] In genetics, an **operon** is a functioning unit of DNA containing a cluster of genes under the control of a single promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The genes are transcribed together into an mRNA strand and either translated together in the cytoplasm, or undergo splicing to create monocistronic mRNAs that are translated separately, i.e. several strands of mRNA that each encode a single gene product.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The result of this is that the genes contained in the operon are either expressed together or not at all.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Several genes must be *co-transcribed* to define an operon.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Originally, operons were thought to exist solely in prokaryotes (which includes organelles like plastids that are derived from bacteria), but their discovery in eukaryotes was shown in the early 1990s, and are considered to be rare.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] In general, expression of prokaryotic operons leads to the generation of polycistronic mRNAs, while eukaryotic operons lead to monocistronic mRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operons are also found in viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] For example, T7 phages have two operons.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The first operon codes for various products, including a special T7 RNA polymerase which can bind to and transcribe the second operon.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The second operon includes a lysis gene whose function is to cause the host cell to burst.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The term "operon" was first proposed in a short paper in the Proceedings of the French Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] From this paper, the so-called general theory of the operon was developed.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] This theory suggested that in all cases, genes within an operon are negatively controlled by a repressor acting at a single operator located before the first gene.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Later, it was discovered that genes could be positively regulated and also regulated at steps that follow transcription initiation.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Therefore, it is not possible to talk of a general regulatory mechanism, because different operons have different mechanisms.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Today, the operon is simply defined as a cluster of genes transcribed into a single mRNA molecule.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Nevertheless, the development of the concept is considered a landmark event in the history of molecular biology.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The first operon to be described was the *lac* operon in *E. coli*.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The 1965 Nobel Prize in Physiology and Medicine was awarded to François Jacob, André Michel Lwoff and Jacques Monod for their discoveries concerning the operon and virus synthesis.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operons occur primarily in prokaryotes but also rarely in some eukaryotes, including nematodes such as *C. elegans* and the fruit fly, *Drosophila melanogaster*. rRNA genes often exist in operons that have been found in a range of eukaryotes including chordates.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] An operon is made up of several structural genes arranged under a common promoter and regulated by a common operator.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] It is defined as a set of adjacent structural genes, plus the adjacent regulatory signals that affect transcription of the structural genes.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The regulators of a given operon, including repressors, corepressors, and activators, are not necessarily coded for by that operon.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The location and condition of the regulators, promoter, operator and structural DNA sequences can determine the effects of common mutations.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operons are related to regulons, stimulons and modulons; whereas operons contain a set of genes regulated by the same operator, regulons contain a set of genes under regulation by a single regulatory protein, and stimulons contain a set of genes under regulation by a single cell stimulus.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] According to its authors, the term "operon" is derived from the verb "to operate".
[src:gene-regulation/operon] An operon contains one or more structural genes which are generally transcribed into one polycistronic mRNA (a single mRNA molecule that codes for more than one protein).
[src:gene-regulation/operon] However, the definition of an operon does not require the mRNA to be polycistronic, though in practice, it usually is.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Upstream of the structural genes lies a promoter sequence which provides a site for RNA polymerase to bind and initiate transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Close to the promoter lies a section of DNA called an *operator*.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] All the structural genes of an operon are turned ON or OFF together, due to a single promoter and operator upstream to them, but sometimes more control over the gene expression is needed.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] To achieve this aspect, some bacterial genes are located near together, but there is a specific promoter for each of them; this is called gene clustering.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Usually these genes encode proteins which will work together in the same pathway, such as a metabolic pathway.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Gene clustering helps a prokaryotic cell to produce metabolic enzymes in a correct order.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Not always included within the operon, but important in its function is a regulatory gene, a constantly expressed gene which codes for repressor proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The regulatory gene does not need to be in, adjacent to, or even near the operon to control it.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] An inducer (small molecule) can displace a repressor (protein) from the operator site (DNA), resulting in an uninhibited operon.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Alternatively, a corepressor can bind to the repressor to allow its binding to the operator site.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] A good example of this type of regulation is seen for the trp operon.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Control of an operon is a type of gene regulation that enables organisms to regulate the expression of various genes depending on environmental conditions.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operon regulation can be either negative or positive by induction or repression.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Negative control involves the binding of a repressor to the operator to prevent transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operons can also be positively controlled.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] With positive control, an activator protein stimulates transcription by binding to DNA (usually at a site other than the operator).
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The *lac* operon of the model bacterium *Escherichia coli* was the first operon to be discovered and provides a typical example of operon function.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] It consists of three adjacent structural genes, a promoter, a terminator, and an operator.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The *lac* operon is regulated by several factors including the availability of glucose and lactose.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Lactose binds to the repressor protein and prevents it from repressing gene transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] This is an example of the derepressible (from above: negative inducible) model.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] So it is a negative inducible operon induced by presence of lactose or allolactose.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Discovered in 1953 by Jacques Monod and colleagues, the trp operon in *E. coli* was the first repressible operon to be discovered.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] While the lac operon can be activated by a chemical (allolactose), the tryptophan (Trp) operon is inhibited by a chemical (tryptophan).
[src:gene-regulation/operon] This operon contains five structural genes: trp E, trp D, trp C, trp B, and trp A, which encodes tryptophan synthetase.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] It also contains a promoter which binds to RNA polymerase and an operator which blocks transcription when bound to the protein synthesized by the repressor gene (trp R) that binds to the operator.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] In the lac operon, lactose binds to the repressor protein and prevents it from repressing gene transcription, while in the trp operon, tryptophan binds to the repressor protein and enables it to repress gene transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Also unlike the lac operon, the trp operon contains a leader peptide and an attenuator sequence which allows for graded regulation.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] This is an example of the corepressible model.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The number and organization of operons has been studied most critically in *E. coli*.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] As a result, predictions can be made based on an organism's genomic sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] One prediction method uses the intergenic distance between reading frames as a primary predictor of the number of operons in the genome.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The separation merely changes the frame and guarantees that the read through is efficient.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Longer stretches exist where operons start and stop, often up to 40–50 bases.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] An alternative method to predict operons is based on finding gene clusters where gene order and orientation is conserved in two or more genomes.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Operon prediction is even more accurate if the functional class of the molecules is considered.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Bacteria have clustered their reading frames into units, sequestered by co-involvement in protein complexes, common pathways, or shared substrates and transporters.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Thus, accurate prediction would involve all of these data, a difficult task indeed.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Pascale Cossart's laboratory was the first to experimentally identify all operons of a microorganism, *Listeria monocytogenes*.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] The 517 polycistronic operons are listed in a 2009 study describing the global changes in transcription that occur in *L. monocytogenes* under different conditions.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Primary promoters are the main controllers of operons.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] However, many operons have internal promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] For example, half of all operons of *E. coli* have internal promoters*.* What happens when both the primary as well as the internal promoters are simultaneously perturbed?
[src:gene-regulation/operon] A recent study followed how each gene in each operon responded to such genome-wide stresses.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] They found that many transcription events of operons end prematurely in those conditions.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] They also found that internal promoters compensate significantly for those terminations creating a wave-like response pattern along operons.
[src:gene-regulation/operon] Next, it was shown that the same occurs in evolutionarily distant bacteria, such as Bacillus subtilis, Corynebacterium glutamicum, and Helicobacter pylori.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In genetics, a **promoter** is a sequence of DNA to which proteins bind to initiate transcription of a single RNA transcript from the DNA downstream of the promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The RNA transcript may encode a protein (mRNA), or can have a function in and of itself, such as tRNA or rRNA.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Promoters are located near the transcription start sites of genes, upstream on the DNA (towards the 5' region of the sense strand).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Promoters can be about 100–1000 base pairs long, the sequence of which is highly dependent on the gene and product of transcription, type or class of RNA polymerase recruited to the site, and species of organism.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] For transcription to take place, the enzyme that synthesizes RNA, known as RNA polymerase, must attach to the DNA near a gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Promoters contain specific DNA sequences such as response elements that provide a secure initial binding site for RNA polymerase and for proteins called transcription factors that recruit RNA polymerase.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] These transcription factors have specific activator or repressor sequences of corresponding nucleotides that attach to specific promoters and regulate gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The promoter resembles a eukaryotic one, though much more simplified.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] It contains BRE and TATA elements and are recognized by TFB and TBP.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Promoters represent critical elements that can work in concert with other regulatory regions (enhancers, silencers, boundary elements/insulators) to direct the level of transcription of a given gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A promoter is induced in response to changes in abundance or conformation of regulatory proteins in a cell, which enable activating transcription factors to recruit RNA polymerase.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Given the short sequences of most promoter elements, promoters can rapidly evolve from random sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] For instance, in *E. coli*, ~60% of random sequences can evolve expression levels comparable to the wild-type lac promoter with only one mutation, and that ~10% of random sequences can serve as active promoters even without evolution.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In bacteria, the promoter contains two short sequence elements approximately 10 (Pribnow Box) and 35 nucleotides *upstream* from the transcription start site.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The above promoter sequences are recognized only by RNA polymerase holoenzyme containing sigma-70.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] RNA polymerase holoenzymes containing other sigma factors recognize different core promoter sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Promoters can be very closely located in the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Such "closely spaced promoters" have been observed in the DNAs of all life forms, from humans to prokaryotes and are highly conserved.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Therefore, they may provide some (presently unknown) advantages.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] These pairs of promoters can be positioned in divergent, tandem, and convergent directions.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] They can also be regulated by transcription factors and differ in various features, such as the nucleotide distance between them, the two promoter strengths, etc.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The most important aspect of two closely spaced promoters is that they will, most likely, interfere with each other.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Several studies have explored this using both analytical and stochastic models.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] There are also studies that measured gene expression in synthetic genes or from one to a few genes controlled by bidirectional promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] More recently, one study measured most genes controlled by tandem promoters in *E. coli*.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In that study, two main forms of interference were measured.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] One is when an RNAP is on the downstream promoter, blocking the movement of RNAPs elongating from the upstream promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The other is when the two promoters are so close that when an RNAP sits on one of the promoters, it blocks any other RNAP from reaching the other promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] These events are possible because the RNAP occupies several nucleotides when bound to the DNA, including in transcription start sites.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Similar events occur when the promoters are in divergent and convergent formations.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The possible events also depend on the distance between them.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Gene promoters are typically located upstream of the gene and can have regulatory elements several kilobases away from the transcriptional start site (enhancers).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In eukaryotes, the transcriptional complex can cause the DNA to bend back on itself, which allows for placement of regulatory sequences far from the actual site of transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Eukaryotic RNA-polymerase-II-dependent promoters can contain a TATA box (consensus sequence TATAAA), which is recognized by the general transcription factor TATA-binding protein (TBP); and a B recognition element (BRE), which is recognized by the general transcription factor TFIIB.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The TATA element and BRE typically are located close to the transcriptional start site (typically within 30 to 40 base pairs).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Eukaryotic promoter regulatory sequences typically bind proteins called transcription factors that are involved in the formation of the transcriptional complex.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] An example is the E-box (sequence CACGTG), which binds transcription factors in the basic helix-loop-helix (bHLH) family (e.g.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Some promoters that are targeted by multiple transcription factors might achieve a hyperactive state, leading to increased transcriptional activity.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Up-regulated expression of genes in mammals is initiated when signals are transmitted to the promoters associated with the genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The presence of multiple methylated CpG sites in CpG islands of promoters causes stable silencing of genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] However, the presence or absence of the other elements have relatively small effects on gene expression in experiments.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Two sequences, the TATA box and Inr, caused small but significant increases in expression (45% and 28% increases, respectively).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The BREu and the BREd elements significantly decreased expression by 35% and 20%, respectively, and the DPE element had no detected effect on expression.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Cis-regulatory modules that are localized in DNA regions distant from the promoters of genes can have very large effects on gene expression, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased expression due to such a cis-regulatory module.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] These cis-regulatory modules include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and coordinate with each other to control expression of their common target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Mediator (coactivator) (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two eRNAs as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating a promoter to initiate transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Bidirectional promoters are short (<1 kbp) intergenic regions of DNA between the 5' ends of the genes in a bidirectional gene pair.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A "bidirectional gene pair" refers to two adjacent genes coded on opposite strands, with their 5' ends oriented toward one another.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The two genes are often functionally related, and modification of their shared promoter region allows them to be co-regulated and thus co-expressed.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Bidirectional promoters are a common feature of mammalian genomes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] About 11% of human genes are bidirectionally paired.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Bidirectionally paired genes in the Gene Ontology database shared at least one database-assigned functional category with their partners 47% of the time.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Microarray analysis has shown bidirectionally paired genes to be co-expressed to a higher degree than random genes or neighboring unidirectional genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Although co-expression does not necessarily indicate co-regulation, methylation of bidirectional promoter regions has been shown to downregulate both genes, and demethylation to upregulate both genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In some cases (about 11%), only one gene of a bidirectional pair is expressed.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In these cases, the promoter is implicated in suppression of the non-expressed gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The mechanism behind this could be competition for the same polymerases, or chromatin modification.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Divergent transcription could shift nucleosomes to upregulate transcription of one gene, or remove bound transcription factors to downregulate transcription of one gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Some functional classes of genes are more likely to be bidirectionally paired than others.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Genes implicated in DNA repair are five times more likely to be regulated by bidirectional promoters than by unidirectional promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Chaperone proteins are three times more likely, and mitochondrial genes are more than twice as likely.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Many basic housekeeping and cellular metabolic genes are regulated by bidirectional promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The overrepresentation of bidirectionally paired DNA repair genes associates these promoters with cancer.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Forty-five percent of human somatic oncogenes seem to be regulated by bidirectional promoters – significantly more than non-cancer causing genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Hypermethylation of the promoters between gene pairs WNT9A/CD558500, CTDSPL/BC040563, and KCNK15/BF195580 has been associated with tumors.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Certain sequence characteristics have been observed in bidirectional promoters, including a lack of TATA boxes, an abundance of CpG islands, and a symmetry around the midpoint of dominant Cs and As on one side and Gs and Ts on the other.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A motif with the consensus sequence of TCTCGCGAGA, also called the CGCG element, was recently shown to drive PolII-driven bidirectional transcription in CpG islands.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] CCAAT boxes are common, as they are in many promoters that lack TATA boxes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In addition, the motifs NRF-1, GABPA, YY1, and ACTACAnnTCCC are represented in bidirectional promoters at significantly higher rates than in unidirectional promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The absence of TATA boxes in bidirectional promoters suggests that TATA boxes play a role in determining the directionality of promoters, but counterexamples of bidirectional promoters do possess TATA boxes and unidirectional promoters without them indicates that they cannot be the only factor.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Although the term "bidirectional promoter" refers specifically to promoter regions of mRNA-encoding genes, luciferase assays have shown that over half of human genes do not have a strong directional bias.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Research suggests that non-coding RNAs are frequently associated with the promoter regions of mRNA-encoding genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] It has been hypothesized that the recruitment and initiation of RNA polymerase II usually begins bidirectionally, but divergent transcription is halted at a checkpoint later during elongation.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Possible mechanisms behind this regulation include sequences in the promoter region, chromatin modification, and the spatial orientation of the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The archaeal promoter resembles a eukaryotic one: a TATA box (at -26/-27) and an upstream BRE (at -33/-34) are commonly found, binding to TBP and TFB (homolog of TFIIB).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] There are also occasionally an initiator element (INR) near the transcription start site [TSS], and a promoter proximal element (PPE) between BRE-TATA and TSS.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] These two are not necessary, but enhance the strength of a promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] TFE (homolog of TFIIE) promotes initiation at suboptimal promoter sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] It binds between -10 and +1, near the Inr.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Strict conservation of these motifs are not necessary, and many archaea with high GC% show "degenerated" TATA boxes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Rather, it's the energetic (duplex enthalpy, duplex stability) and structural (intrinsic curvature, bendability) features of the promoter that mainly matter.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A subgenomic promoter is a promoter added to a virus for a specific heterologous gene, resulting in the formation of mRNA for that gene alone.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Many positive-sense RNA viruses produce these subgenomic mRNAs (sgRNA) as one of the common infection techniques used by these viruses and generally transcribe late viral genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Subgenomic promoters range from 24 nucleotide (Sindbis virus) to over 100 nucleotides (Beet necrotic yellow vein virus) and are usually found upstream of the transcription start.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A wide variety of algorithms have been developed to facilitate detection of promoters in genomic sequence, and promoter prediction is a common element of many gene prediction methods.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A bacterial promoter region is located before the -35 and -10 Consensus sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The closer the promoter region is to the consensus sequences the more often transcription of that gene will take place.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] There is not a set pattern for promoter regions as there are for consensus sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] One approach is to use a biophysical theory of why promoters work.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] For archaea, a combination of calculated energetic and structural features can detect promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] For bacteria, a biophysical model that estimates RNAP-sigma70 binding probability can detect and estimate the strengths of promoters.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Another approach is to use a pattern-matching program based on known promoters, from simple hand-crafted regular expressions to advanced machine learning methods such as decision trees, hidden Markov models (HMM), and neural networks.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] YAPP, an 2000s eukaryotic core-promoter prediction program, uses HMM.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A 2017 publication predicts bacterial and eukaryotic promoters using a convolutional neural network.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The promoter binding process is crucial in the understanding of the process of gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Tuning synthetic genetic systems relies on precisely engineered synthetic promoters with known levels of transcription rates.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Although RNA polymerase holoenzyme shows high affinity to non-specific sites of the DNA, this characteristic does not allow us to clarify the process of promoter location.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] This process of promoter location has been attributed to the structure of the holoenzyme to DNA and sigma 4 to DNA complexes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Most diseases are heterogeneous in cause, meaning that one "disease" is often many different diseases at the molecular level, though symptoms exhibited and response to treatment may be identical.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] How diseases of different molecular origin respond to treatments is partially addressed in the discipline of pharmacogenomics.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Not listed here are the many kinds of cancers involving aberrant transcriptional regulation owing to creation of chimeric genes through pathological chromosomal translocation.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Importantly, intervention in the number or structure of promoter-bound proteins is one key to treating a disease without affecting expression of unrelated genes sharing elements with the target gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Some genes whose change is not desirable are capable of influencing the potential of a cell to become cancerous.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In humans, about 70% of promoters located near the transcription start site of a gene (proximal promoters) contain a CpG island.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] CpG islands are generally 200 to 2000 base pairs long, have a C:G base pair content >50%, and have regions of DNA where a cytosine nucleotide is followed by a guanine nucleotide and this occurs frequently in the linear sequence of bases along its 5' → 3' direction.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Distal promoters also frequently contain CpG islands, such as the promoter of the DNA repair gene *ERCC1*, where the CpG island-containing promoter is located about 5,400 nucleotides upstream of the coding region of the *ERCC1* gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] CpG islands also occur frequently in promoters for functional noncoding RNAs such as microRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In humans, DNA methylation occurs at the 5' position of the pyrimidine ring of the cytosine residues within CpG sites to form 5-methylcytosines.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Silencing of a gene may be initiated by other mechanisms, but this is often followed by methylation of CpG sites in the promoter CpG island to cause the stable silencing of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Generally, in progression to cancer, hundreds of genes are silenced or activated.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Although silencing of some genes in cancers occurs by mutation, a large proportion of carcinogenic gene silencing is a result of altered DNA methylation (see DNA methylation in cancer).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] DNA methylation causing silencing in cancer typically occurs at multiple CpG sites in the CpG islands that are present in the promoters of protein coding genes.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Altered expressions of microRNAs also silence or activate many genes in progression to cancer (see microRNAs in cancer).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Altered microRNA expression occurs through hyper/hypo-methylation of CpG sites in CpG islands in promoters controlling transcription of the microRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Silencing of DNA repair genes through methylation of CpG islands in their promoters appears to be especially important in progression to cancer (see methylation of DNA repair genes in cancer).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] The usage of the term canonical sequence to refer to a promoter is often problematic, and can lead to misunderstandings about promoter sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Canonical implies perfect, in some sense.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In the case of a transcription factor binding site, there may be a single sequence that binds the protein most strongly under specified cellular conditions.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] However, natural selection may favor less energetic binding as a way of regulating transcriptional output.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] In this case, we may call the most common sequence in a population the wild-type sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] It may not even be the most advantageous sequence to have under prevailing conditions.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Recent evidence also indicates that several genes (including the proto-oncogene c-myc) have G-quadruplex motifs as potential regulatory signals.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Some cases of many genetic diseases are associated with variations in promoters or transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Some promoters are called constitutive as they are active in all circumstances in the cell, while others are regulated, becoming active in the cell only in response to specific stimuli.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] A tissue-specific promoter is a promoter that has activity in only certain cell types.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] When referring to a promoter some authors actually mean promoter + operator; i.e., the lac promoter is IPTG inducible, meaning that besides the lac promoter, the lac operon is also present.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] If the lac operator were not present the IPTG would not have an inducible effect.
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Another example is the Tac-Promoter system (Ptac).
[src:gene-regulation/promoter-genetics] Notice how tac is written as a tac promoter, while in fact tac is actually both a promoter and an operator.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Gene regulation is essential for viruses, prokaryotes and eukaryotes as it increases the versatility and adaptability of an organism by allowing the cell to express protein when needed.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In multicellular organisms, gene regulation drives cellular differentiation and morphogenesis in the embryo, leading to the creation of different cell types that possess different gene expression profiles from the same genome sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Although this does not explain how gene regulation originated, evolutionary biologists include it as a partial explanation of how evolution works at a molecular level, and it is central to the science of evolutionary developmental biology ("evo-devo").
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Any step of gene expression may be modulated, from signaling to transcription to post-translational modification of a protein.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In eukaryotes, the accessibility of large regions of DNA can depend on its chromatin structure, which can be altered as a result of histone modifications directed by DNA methylation, ncRNA, or DNA-binding protein.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Hence these modifications may up or down regulate the expression of a gene.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Some of these modifications that regulate gene expression are inheritable and are referred to as epigenetic regulation.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Transcription of DNA is dictated by its structure.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In general, the density of its packing is indicative of the frequency of transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Such modifications are considered to be responsible for more or less permanent changes in gene expression levels.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Methylation of DNA is a common method of gene silencing.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] DNA is typically methylated by methyltransferase enzymes on cytosine nucleotides in a CpG dinucleotide sequence (also called "CpG islands" when densely clustered).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Analysis of the pattern of methylation in a given region of DNA (which can be a promoter) can be achieved through a method called bisulfite mapping.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Methylated cytosine residues are unchanged by the treatment, whereas unmethylated ones are changed to uracil.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The differences are analyzed by DNA sequencing or by methods developed to quantify SNPs, such as Pyrosequencing (Biotage) or MassArray (Sequenom), measuring the relative amounts of C/T at the CG dinucleotide.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Abnormal methylation patterns are thought to be involved in oncogenesis.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Histone acetylation is also an important process in transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Histone acetyltransferase enzymes (HATs) such as CREB-binding protein also dissociate the DNA from the histone complex, allowing transcription to proceed.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Often, DNA methylation and histone deacetylation work together in gene silencing.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The combination of the two seems to be a signal for DNA to be packed more densely, lowering gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Regulation of transcription thus controls when transcription occurs and how much RNA is created.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Transcription of a gene by RNA polymerase can be regulated by several mechanisms.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Specificity factors alter the specificity of RNA polymerase for a given promoter or set of promoters, making it more or less likely to bind to them (i.e., sigma factors used in prokaryotic transcription).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Repressors bind to the Operator, coding sequences on the DNA strand that are close to or overlapping the promoter region, impeding RNA polymerase's progress along the strand, thus impeding the expression of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The image to the right demonstrates regulation by a repressor in the lac operon.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] General transcription factors position RNA polymerase at the start of a protein-coding sequence and then release the polymerase to transcribe the mRNA.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Activators enhance the interaction between RNA polymerase and a particular promoter, encouraging the expression of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Activators do this by increasing the attraction of RNA polymerase for the promoter, through interactions with subunits of the RNA polymerase or indirectly by changing the structure of the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Enhancers are sites on the DNA helix that are bound by activators in order to loop the DNA bringing a specific promoter to the initiation complex.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Enhancers are much more common in eukaryotes than prokaryotes, where only a few examples exist (to date).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Silencers are regions of DNA sequences that, when bound by particular transcription factors, can silence expression of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] RNA can be an important regulator of gene activity, e.g. by microRNA (miRNA), antisense-RNA, or long non-coding RNA (lncRNA).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] LncRNAs differ from mRNAs in the sense that they have specified subcellular locations and functions.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] They were first discovered to be located in the nucleus and chromatin, and the localizations and functions are highly diverse now.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Some still reside in chromatin where they interact with proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] While this lncRNA ultimately affects gene expression in neuronal disorders such as Parkinson, Huntington, and Alzheimer disease, others, such as, PNCTR(pyrimidine-rich non-coding transcriptors), play a role in lung cancer.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Given their role in disease, lncRNAs are potential biomarkers and may be useful targets for drugs or gene therapy, although there are no approved drugs that target lncRNAs yet.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The number of lncRNAs in the human genome remains poorly defined, but some estimates range from 16,000 to 100,000 lnc genes.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Epigenetics refers to the modification of genes that is not changing the DNA or RNA sequence.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Epigenetic modifications are also a key factor in influencing gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] They occur on genomic DNA and histones and their chemical modifications regulate gene expression in a more efficient manner.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] There are several modifications of DNA (usually methylation) and more than 100 modifications of RNA in mammalian cells." Those modifications result in altered protein binding to DNA and a change in RNA stability and translation efficiency.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In vertebrates, the majority of gene promoters contain a CpG island with numerous CpG sites.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] When many of a gene's promoter CpG sites are methylated the gene becomes silenced.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Colorectal cancers typically have 3 to 6 driver mutations and 33 to 66 hitchhiker or passenger mutations.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] However, transcriptional silencing may be of more importance than mutation in causing progression to cancer.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] For example, in colorectal cancers about 600 to 800 genes are transcriptionally silenced by CpG island methylation (see regulation of transcription in cancer).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Transcriptional repression in cancer can also occur by other epigenetic mechanisms, such as altered expression of microRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In breast cancer, transcriptional repression of BRCA1 may occur more frequently by over-expressed microRNA-182 than by hypermethylation of the BRCA1 promoter (see Low expression of BRCA1 in breast and ovarian cancers).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] One of the cardinal features of addiction is its persistence.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The persistent behavioral changes appear to be due to long-lasting changes, resulting from epigenetic alterations affecting gene expression, within particular regions of the brain.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Drugs of abuse cause three types of epigenetic alteration in the brain.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] These are (1) histone acetylations and histone methylations, (2) DNA methylation at CpG sites, and (3) epigenetic downregulation or upregulation of microRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Chronic nicotine intake in mice alters brain cell epigenetic control of gene expression through acetylation of histones.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] This increases expression in the brain of the protein FosB, important in addiction.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Cigarette addiction was also studied in about 16,000 humans, including never smokers, current smokers, and those who had quit smoking for up to 30 years.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In blood cells, more than 18,000 CpG sites (of the roughly 450,000 analyzed CpG sites in the genome) had frequently altered methylation among current smokers.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] These CpG sites occurred in over 7,000 genes, or roughly a third of known human genes.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The majority of the differentially methylated CpG sites returned to the level of never-smokers within five years of smoking cessation.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] However, 2,568 CpGs among 942 genes remained differentially methylated in former versus never smokers.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Such remaining epigenetic changes can be viewed as "molecular scars" that may affect gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In rodent models, drugs of abuse, including cocaine, methamphetamine, alcohol and tobacco smoke products, all cause DNA damage in the brain.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] During repair of DNA damages some individual repair events can alter the methylation of DNA and/or the acetylations or methylations of histones at the sites of damage, and thus can contribute to leaving an epigenetic scar on chromatin.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Such epigenetic scars likely contribute to the persistent epigenetic changes found in addiction.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In mammals, methylation of cytosine (see Figure) in DNA is a major regulatory mediator.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Methylated cytosines primarily occur in dinucleotide sequences where cytosine is followed by a guanine, a CpG site.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The total number of CpG sites in the human genome is approximately 28 million. and generally about 70% of all CpG sites have a methylated cytosine.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In a rat, a painful learning experience, contextual fear conditioning, can result in a life-long fearful memory after a single training event.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Cytosine methylation is altered in the promoter regions of about 9.17% of all genes in the hippocampus neuron DNA of a rat that has been subjected to a brief fear conditioning experience.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The hippocampus is where new memories are initially stored.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Methylation of CpGs in a promoter region of a gene represses transcription while methylation of CpGs in the body of a gene increases expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] TET enzymes play a central role in demethylation of methylated cytosines.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Demethylation of CpGs in a gene promoter by TET enzyme activity increases transcription of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] When contextual fear conditioning is applied to a rat, more than 5,000 differentially methylated regions (DMRs) (of 500 nucleotides each) occur in the rat hippocampus neural genome both one hour and 24 hours after the conditioning in the hippocampus.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] This causes about 500 genes to be up-regulated (often due to demethylation of CpG sites in a promoter region) and about 1,000 genes to be down-regulated (often due to newly formed 5-methylcytosine at CpG sites in a promoter region).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The pattern of induced and repressed genes within neurons appears to provide a molecular basis for forming the first transient memory of this training event in the hippocampus of the rat brain.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] After the DNA is transcribed and mRNA is formed, there must be some sort of regulation on how much the mRNA is translated into proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Cells do this by modulating the capping, splicing, addition of a Poly(A) Tail, the sequence-specific nuclear export rates, and, in several contexts, sequestration of the RNA transcript.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] These processes occur in eukaryotes but not in prokaryotes.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] This modulation is a result of a protein or transcript that, in turn, is regulated and may have an affinity for certain sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Three prime untranslated regions (3'-UTRs) of messenger RNAs (mRNAs) often contain regulatory sequences that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Such 3'-UTRs often contain both binding sites for microRNAs (miRNAs) as well as for regulatory proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] By binding to specific sites within the 3'-UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The 3'-UTR also may have silencer regions that bind repressor proteins that inhibit the expression of a mRNA.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The 3'-UTR often contains miRNA response elements (MREs).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] MREs are sequences to which miRNAs bind.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] These are prevalent motifs within 3'-UTRs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Among all regulatory motifs within the 3'-UTRs (e.g. including silencer regions), MREs make up about half of the motifs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] As of 2014, the miRBase web site, an archive of miRNA sequences and annotations, listed 28,645 entries in 233 biologic species.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Of these, 1,881 miRNAs were in annotated human miRNA loci. miRNAs were predicted to have an average of about four hundred target mRNAs (affecting expression of several hundred genes).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Freidman et al. estimate that >45,000 miRNA target sites within human mRNA 3'-UTRs are conserved above background levels, and >60% of human protein-coding genes have been under selective pressure to maintain pairing to miRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Direct experiments show that a single miRNA can reduce the stability of hundreds of unique mRNAs.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Other experiments show that a single miRNA may repress the production of hundreds of proteins, but that this repression often is relatively mild (less than 2-fold).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression seem to be important in cancer.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] For instance, in gastrointestinal cancers, a 2015 paper identified nine miRNAs as epigenetically altered and effective in down-regulating DNA repair enzymes.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression also seem to be important in neuropsychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, major depressive disorder, Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease and autism spectrum disorders.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The translation of mRNA can also be controlled by a number of mechanisms, mostly at the level of initiation.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Recruitment of the small ribosomal subunit can indeed be modulated by mRNA secondary structure, antisense RNA binding, or protein binding.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In both prokaryotes and eukaryotes, a large number of RNA binding proteins exist, which often are directed to their target sequence by the secondary structure of the transcript, which may change depending on certain conditions, such as temperature or presence of a ligand (aptamer).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Some transcripts act as ribozymes and self-regulate their expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] A large number of studied regulatory systems come from developmental biology.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Up-regulation is a process which occurs within a cell triggered by a signal (originating internal or external to the cell), which results in increased expression of one or more genes and as a result the proteins encoded by those genes.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] Conversely, down-regulation is a process resulting in decreased gene and corresponding protein expression.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] The GAL4/UAS system is an example of both an inducible and repressible system.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] **Gal4** binds an upstream activation sequence (UAS) to activate the transcription of the GAL1/GAL7/GAL10 cassette.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] On the other hand, a MIG1 response to the presence of glucose can inhibit GAL4 and therefore stop the expression of the GAL1/GAL7/GAL10 cassette.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] In general, most experiments investigating differential expression used whole cell extracts of RNA, called steady-state levels, to determine which genes changed and by how much.
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] These are, however, not informative of where the regulation has occurred and may mask conflicting regulatory processes (*see post-transcriptional regulation*), but it is still the most commonly analysed (quantitative PCR and DNA microarray).
[src:gene-regulation/regulation-of-gene-expression] When studying gene expression, there are several methods to look at the various stages.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In molecular genetics, a **repressor** is a DNA- or RNA-binding protein that inhibits the expression of one or more genes by binding to the operator or associated silencers.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] A DNA-binding repressor blocks the attachment of RNA polymerase to the promoter, thus preventing transcription of the genes into messenger RNA.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] An RNA-binding repressor binds to the mRNA and prevents translation of the mRNA into protein.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] If an inducer, a molecule that initiates the gene expression, is present, then it can interact with the repressor protein and detach it from the operator.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] RNA polymerase then can transcribe the message (expressing the gene).
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] A co-repressor is a molecule that can bind to the repressor and make it bind to the operator tightly, which decreases transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] A repressor that binds with a co-repressor is termed an *aporepressor* or *inactive repressor*.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] One type of aporepressor is the trp repressor, an important metabolic protein in bacteria.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The above mechanism of repression is a type of feedback mechanism because it only allows transcription to occur if a certain condition is present: the presence of specific inducer(s).
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In contrast, an active repressor binds directly to an operator to repress gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] While repressors are more commonly found in prokaryotes, they are rare in eukaryotes.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Furthermore, most known eukaryotic repressors are found in simple organisms (e.g., yeast), and act by interacting directly with activators.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] This contrasts prokaryotic repressors which can also alter DNA or RNA structure.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Within the eukaryotic genome are regions of DNA known as silencers.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] These are DNA sequences that bind to repressors to partially or fully repress a gene.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Silencers can be located several bases upstream or downstream from the actual promoter of the gene.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Repressors can also have two binding sites: one for the silencer region and one for the promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] This causes chromosome looping, allowing the promoter region and the silencer region to come in proximity of each other.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The *lacZYA* operon houses genes encoding proteins needed for lactose breakdown.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The *lacI* gene codes for a protein called "the repressor" or "the lac repressor", which functions to repressor of the lac operon.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The gene *lacI* is situated immediately upstream of *lacZYA* but is transcribed from a *lacI* promoter.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The *lacI* gene synthesizes LacI repressor protein.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The LacI repressor protein represses *lacZYA* by binding to the operator sequence *lacO*.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The *lac* repressor is constitutively expressed and usually bound to the operator region of the promoter, which interferes with the ability of RNA polymerase (RNAP) to begin transcription of the *lac* operon.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In the presence of the inducer allolactose, the repressor changes conformation, reduces its DNA binding strength and dissociates from the operator DNA sequence in the promoter region of the lac operon.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] RNAP is then able to bind to the promoter and begin transcription of the *lacZYA* gene.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] An example of a repressor protein is the methionine repressor MetJ.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] MetJ interacts with DNA bases via a ribbon-helix-helix (RHH) motif.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] MetJ is a homodimer consisting of two monomers, which each provides a beta ribbon and an alpha helix.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Together, the beta ribbons of each monomer come together to form an antiparallel beta-sheet which binds to the DNA operator ("Met box") in its major groove.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Once bound, the MetJ dimer interacts with another MetJ dimer bound to the complementary strand of the operator via its alpha helices.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] AdoMet binds to a pocket in MetJ that *does not* overlap the site of DNA binding.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The Met box has the DNA sequence AGACGTCT, a palindrome (it shows dyad symmetry) allowing the same sequence to be recognized on either strand of the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The junction between C and G in the middle of the Met box contains a pyrimidine-purine step that becomes positively supercoiled forming a kink in the phosphodiester backbone.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] This is how the protein checks for the recognition site as it allows the DNA duplex to follow the shape of the protein.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In other words, recognition happens through indirect readout of the structural parameters of the DNA, rather than via specific base sequence recognition.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Each MetJ dimer contains two binding sites for the cofactor S-Adenosyl methionine (SAM) which is a product in the biosynthesis of methionine.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] When SAM is present, it binds to the MetJ protein, increasing its affinity for its cognate operator site, which halts transcription of genes involved in methionine synthesis.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] When SAM concentration becomes low, the repressor dissociates from the operator site, allowing more methionine to be produced.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The L-arabinose operon houses genes coding for arabinose-digesting enzymes.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] These function to break down arabinose as an alternative source for energy when glucose is low or absent.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The operon consists of a regulatory repressor gene (araC), three control sites (ara02, ara01, araI1, and araI2), two promoters (Parac/ParaBAD) and three structural genes (araBAD).
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Once produced, araC acts as repressor by binding to the araI region to form a loop which prevents polymerases from binding to the promotor and transcribing the structural genes into proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In the absence of Arabinose and araC (repressor), loop formation is not initiated and structural gene expression will be lower.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In the absence of Arabinose but presence of araC, araC regions form dimers, and bind to bring ara02 and araI1 domains closer by loop formation.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] In the presence of both Arabinose and araC, araC binds with the arabinose and acts as an activator.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] This conformational change in the araC no longer can form a loop, and the linear gene segment promotes RNA polymerase recruitment to the structural araBAD region.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The FLC operon is a conserved eukaryotic locus that is negatively associated with flowering via repression of genes needed for the development of the meristem to switch to a floral state in the plant species *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] FLC expression has been shown be regulated by the presence of FRIGIDA, and negatively correlates with decreases in temperature resulting in the prevention of vernalization.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The degree to which expression decreases depends on the temperature and exposure time as seasons progress.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] After the downregulation of FLC expression, the potential for flowering is enabled.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] The regulation of FLC expression involves both genetic and epigenetic factors such as histone methylation and DNA methylation.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] Furthermore, a number of genes are cofactors act as negative transcription factors for FLC genes.
[src:gene-regulation/repressor] FLC genes also have a large number of homologues across species that allow for specific adaptations in a range of climates.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In molecular biology, a **transcription factor** (**TF**) (or **sequence-specific DNA-binding factor**) is a protein that controls the rate of transcription of genetic information from DNA to messenger RNA, by binding to DNA sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Specificity can be due to sequence motifs, or epigenetic modifications.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The function of TFs is to regulate—turn on and off—genes in order to make sure that they are expressed in the desired cells at the right time and in the right amount throughout the life of the cell and the organism.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Groups of TFs function in a coordinated fashion to direct cell division, cell growth, and cell death throughout life; cell migration and organization (body plan) during embryonic development; and intermittently in response to signals from outside the cell, such as a hormone.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] There are approximately 1600 TFs in the human genome, where half of them are C2H2 zinc fingers.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are members of the proteome as well as regulome.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TFs work alone or with other proteins in a complex, by promoting (as an activator), or blocking (as a repressor) the recruitment of RNA polymerase (the enzyme that performs the transcription of genetic information from DNA to RNA) to specific genes.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] A defining feature of TFs is that they contain at least one DNA-binding domain (DBD), which attaches to a specific sequence of DNA adjacent to the genes that they regulate.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TFs are grouped into classes based on their DBDs.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Other proteins such as coactivators, chromatin remodelers, histone acetyltransferases, histone deacetylases, kinases, and methylases are also essential to gene regulation, but lack DNA-binding domains, and therefore are not TFs.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TFs are of interest in medicine because TF mutations can cause specific diseases, and medications can be potentially targeted toward them.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are essential for the regulation of gene expression and are, as a consequence, found in all living organisms.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The number of transcription factors found within an organism increases with genome size, and larger genomes tend to have more transcription factors per gene.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] There are approximately 2800 proteins in the human genome that contain DNA-binding domains, and 1600 of these are presumed to function as transcription factors, where half of them (~800) are C2H2 zinc finger proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Therefore, approximately 10% of genes in the genome code for transcription factors, which makes this family the single largest family of human proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Furthermore, genes are often flanked by several binding sites for distinct transcription factors, and efficient expression of each of these genes requires the cooperative action of several different transcription factors (see, for example, hepatocyte nuclear factors).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Hence, the combinatorial use of a subset of the approximately 2000 human transcription factors easily accounts for the unique regulation of each gene in the human genome during development.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors bind to either enhancer or promoter regions of DNA adjacent to the genes that they regulate based on recognizing specific DNA motifs.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Depending on the transcription factor, the transcription of the adjacent gene is either up- or down-regulated.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors use a variety of mechanisms for the regulation of gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are one of the groups of proteins that read and interpret the genetic "blueprint" in the DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] They bind to the DNA and help initiate a program of increased or decreased gene transcription.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] As such, they are vital for many important cellular processes.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, an important class of transcription factors called general transcription factors (GTFs) are necessary for transcription to occur.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many of these GTFs do not actually bind DNA, but rather are part of the large transcription preinitiation complex that interacts with RNA polymerase directly.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The most common GTFs are TFIIA, TFIIB, TFIID (see also TATA binding protein), TFIIE, TFIIF, and TFIIH.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The preinitiation complex binds to promoter regions of DNA upstream to the gene that they regulate.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Other transcription factors differentially regulate the expression of various genes by binding to enhancer regions of DNA adjacent to regulated genes.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] These transcription factors are critical to making sure that genes are expressed in the right cell at the right time and in the right amount, depending on the changing requirements of the organism.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors in multicellular organisms are involved in development.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Responding to stimuli, these transcription factors turn on/off the transcription of the appropriate genes, which, in turn, allows for changes in cell morphology or activities needed for cell fate determination and cellular differentiation.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The Hox transcription factor family, for example, is important for proper body pattern formation in organisms as diverse as fruit flies to humans.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Another example is the transcription factor encoded by the sex-determining region Y (SRY) gene, which plays a major role in determining sex in humans.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Cells can communicate with each other by releasing molecules that produce signaling cascades within another receptive cell.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] If the signal requires upregulation or downregulation of genes in the recipient cell, often transcription factors will be downstream in the signaling cascade.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The estrogen receptor then goes to the cell's nucleus and binds to its DNA-binding sites, changing the transcriptional regulation of the associated genes.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Not only do transcription factors act downstream of signaling cascades related to biological stimuli but they can also be downstream of signaling cascades involved in environmental stimuli.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors, especially some that are proto-oncogenes or tumor suppressors, help regulate the cell cycle and as such determine how large a cell will get and when it can divide into two daughter cells.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] One example is the Myc oncogene, which has important roles in cell growth and apoptosis.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors can also be used to alter gene expression in a host cell to promote pathogenesis.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] A well studied example of this are the transcription-activator like effectors (TAL effectors) secreted by Xanthomonas bacteria.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] When injected into plants, these proteins can enter the nucleus of the plant cell, bind plant promoter sequences, and activate transcription of plant genes that aid in bacterial infection.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TAL effectors contain a central repeat region in which there is a simple relationship between the identity of two critical residues in sequential repeats and sequential DNA bases in the TAL effector's target site.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This property likely makes it easier for these proteins to evolve in order to better compete with the defense mechanisms of the host cell.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] It is common in biology for important processes to have multiple layers of regulation and control.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This is also true with transcription factors: Not only do transcription factors control the rates of transcription to regulate the amounts of gene products (RNA and protein) available to the cell but transcription factors themselves are regulated (often by other transcription factors).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors (like all proteins) are transcribed from a gene on a chromosome into RNA, and then the RNA is translated into protein.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Any of these steps can be regulated to affect the production (and thus activity) of a transcription factor.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] An implication of this is that transcription factors can regulate themselves.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] For example, in a negative feedback loop, the transcription factor acts as its own repressor: If the transcription factor protein binds the DNA of its own gene, it down-regulates the production of more of itself.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This is one mechanism to maintain low levels of a transcription factor in a cell.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, transcription factors (like most proteins) are transcribed in the nucleus but are then translated in the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many proteins that are active in the nucleus contain nuclear localization signals that direct them to the nucleus.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] But, for many transcription factors, this is a key point in their regulation.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Important classes of transcription factors such as some nuclear receptors must first bind a ligand while in the cytoplasm before they can relocate to the nucleus.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors may be activated or deactivated through their signal-sensing or effector domains.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] However, not all transcription factors have an effector domain; for example, approximately 400 C2H2 zinc finger transcription factors contain only DNA-binding domains (DBDs).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, DNA is organized with the help of histones into compact particles called nucleosomes, where sequences of about 147 DNA base pairs make ~1.65 turns around histone protein octamers.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] DNA within nucleosomes is inaccessible to many transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Some transcription factors, so-called pioneer factors are still able to bind their DNA binding sites on the nucleosomal DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] For most other transcription factors, the nucleosome should be actively unwound by molecular motors such as chromatin remodelers.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Alternatively, the nucleosome can be partially unwrapped by thermal fluctuations, allowing temporary access to the transcription factor binding site.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In many cases, a transcription factor needs to compete for binding to its DNA binding site with other transcription factors and histones or non-histone chromatin proteins.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Pairs of transcription factors and other proteins can play antagonistic roles (activator versus repressor) in the regulation of the same gene.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Most transcription factors do not work alone.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many large TF families form complex homotypic or heterotypic interactions through dimerization.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] For gene transcription to occur, a number of transcription factors must bind to DNA regulatory sequences.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This collection of transcription factors, in turn, recruit intermediary proteins such as cofactors that allow efficient recruitment of the preinitiation complex and RNA polymerase.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Thus, for a single transcription factor to initiate transcription, all of these other proteins must also be present, and the transcription factor must be in a state where it can bind to them if necessary.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Cofactors are proteins that modulate the effects of transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Cofactors are interchangeable between specific gene promoters; the protein complex that occupies the promoter DNA and the amino acid sequence of the cofactor determine its spatial conformation.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] For example, certain steroid receptors can exchange cofactors with NF-κB, which is a switch between inflammation and cellular differentiation; thereby steroids can affect the inflammatory response and function of certain tissues.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors and methylated cytosines in DNA both have major roles in regulating gene expression.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] (Methylation of cytosine in DNA primarily occurs where cytosine is followed by guanine in the 5' to 3' DNA sequence, a CpG site.) Methylation of CpG sites in a promoter region of a gene usually represses gene transcription, while methylation of CpGs in the body of a gene increases expression.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The DNA binding sites of 519 transcription factors were evaluated.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Of these, 169 transcription factors (33%) did not have CpG dinucleotides in their binding sites, and 33 transcription factors (6%) could bind to a CpG-containing motif but did not display a preference for a binding site with either a methylated or unmethylated CpG.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TET enzymes do not specifically bind to methylcytosine except when recruited (see DNA demethylation).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] TET-mediated conversion of mC to hmC appears to disrupt the binding of 5mC-binding proteins including MECP2 and MBD (Methyl-CpG-binding domain) proteins, facilitating nucleosome remodeling and the binding of transcription factors, thereby activating transcription of those genes.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] EGR1 is an important transcription factor in memory formation.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] It has an essential role in brain neuron epigenetic reprogramming.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The transcription factor EGR1 recruits the TET1 protein that initiates a pathway of DNA demethylation.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] EGR1, together with TET1, is employed in programming the distribution of methylation sites on brain DNA during brain development and in learning (see Epigenetics in learning and memory).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The portion (domain) of the transcription factor that binds DNA is called its DNA-binding domain.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The DNA sequence that a transcription factor binds to is called a transcription factor-binding site or response element.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors interact with their binding sites using a combination of electrostatic (of which hydrogen bonds are a special case) and Van der Waals forces.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Due to the nature of these chemical interactions, most transcription factors bind DNA in a sequence specific manner.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] However, not all bases in the transcription factor-binding site may actually interact with the transcription factor.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In addition, some of these interactions may be weaker than others.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Thus, transcription factors do not bind just one sequence but are capable of binding a subset of closely related sequences, each with a different strength of interaction.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] For example, although the consensus binding site for the TATA-binding protein (TBP) is TATAAAA, the TBP transcription factor can also bind similar sequences such as TATATAT or TATATAA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Because transcription factors can bind a set of related sequences and these sequences tend to be short, potential transcription factor binding sites can occur by chance if the DNA sequence is long enough.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] It is unlikely, however, that a transcription factor will bind all compatible sequences in the genome of the cell.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Other constraints, such as DNA accessibility in the cell or availability of cofactors may also help dictate where a transcription factor will actually bind.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Thus, given the genome sequence, it is still difficult to predict where a transcription factor will actually bind in a living cell.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Additional recognition specificity, however, may be obtained through the use of more than one DNA-binding domain (for example tandem DBDs in the same transcription factor or through dimerization of two transcription factors) that bind to two or more adjacent sequences of DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are of clinical significance for at least two reasons: (1) mutations can be associated with specific diseases, and (2) they can be targets of medications.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Due to their important roles in development, intercellular signaling, and cell cycle, some human diseases have been associated with mutations in transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors are either tumor suppressors or oncogenes, and, thus, mutations or aberrant regulation of them is associated with cancer.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Three groups of transcription factors are known to be important in human cancer: (1) the NF-kappaB and AP-1 families, (2) the STAT family and (3) the steroid receptors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Approximately 10% of currently prescribed drugs directly target the nuclear receptor class of transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Examples include tamoxifen and bicalutamide for the treatment of breast and prostate cancer, respectively, and various types of anti-inflammatory and anabolic steroids.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In addition, transcription factors are often indirectly modulated by drugs through signaling cascades.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] It might be possible to directly target other less-explored transcription factors such as NF-κB with drugs.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors outside the nuclear receptor family are thought to be more difficult to target with small molecule therapeutics since it is not clear that they are "drugable" but progress has been made on Pax2 and the notch pathway.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Gene duplications have played a crucial role in the evolution of species.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This applies particularly to transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Once they occur as duplicates, accumulated mutations encoding for one copy can take place without negatively affecting the regulation of downstream targets.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] However, changes of the DNA binding specificities of the single-copy Leafy transcription factor, which occurs in most land plants, have recently been elucidated.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] In that respect, a single-copy transcription factor can undergo a change of specificity through a promiscuous intermediate without losing function.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Similar mechanisms have been proposed in the context of all alternative phylogenetic hypotheses, and the role of transcription factors in the evolution of all species.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The transcription factors have a role in resistance activity which is important for successful biocontrol activity.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] There are different technologies available to analyze transcription factors.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] On the genomic level, DNA-sequencing and database research are commonly used.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The protein version of the transcription factor is detectable by using specific antibodies.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The sample is detected on a western blot.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] By using electrophoretic mobility shift assay (EMSA), the activation profile of transcription factors can be detected.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] A multiplex approach for activation profiling is a TF chip system where several different transcription factors can be detected in parallel.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The most commonly used method for identifying transcription factor binding sites is chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP).
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] This technique relies on chemical fixation of chromatin with formaldehyde, followed by co-precipitation of DNA and the transcription factor of interest using an antibody that specifically targets that protein.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The DNA sequences can then be identified by microarray or high-throughput sequencing (ChIP-seq) to determine transcription factor binding sites.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] If no antibody is available for the protein of interest, DamID may be a convenient alternative.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] As described in more detail below, transcription factors may be classified by their (1) mechanism of action, (2) regulatory function, or (3) sequence homology (and hence structural similarity) in their DNA-binding domains.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] They are also classified by 3D structure of their DBD and the way it contacts DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are often classified based on the sequence similarity and hence the tertiary structure of their DNA-binding domains.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] The following classification is based on the 3D structure of their DBD and the way it contacts DNA.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] It was first developed for Human TF and later extended to rodents and also to plants.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] There are numerous databases cataloging information about transcription factors, but their scope and utility vary dramatically.
[src:gene-regulation/transcription-factor] Some may contain only information about the actual proteins, some about their binding sites, or about their target genes.
